3:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Bluefin calculates funding rates hourly based on the premium between perpetual and spot prices, with payments exchanged between long and short positions at settlement. The exchange uses an order book model with maker fees at 0.02% and taker fees at 0.05%, significantly lower than many centralized competitors. Settlement occurs on-chain through Sui's high-performance consensus, ensuring fast execution and transparent rate calculations. Position holders receive or pay funding based on their side relative to the market premium."}]
4:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","DOT","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"DOT's strong institutional adoption and active staking ecosystem create persistent funding rate patterns as traders hedge exposure to parachain auctions and staking rewards. The token's large market cap ensures sufficient liquidity depth on Bluefin for meaningful arbitrage positions. DOT's correlation with broader Layer 1 narratives makes it an excellent hedge for portfolio-level funding strategies."}]]}]
5:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"DOT Funding Rate Historical Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"DOT funding rates on Bluefin typically range from -0.01% to 0.05% hourly, with notable spikes during parachain auction periods and Polkadot ecosystem developments. Negative rates often emerge during bear market phases when shorts dominate, creating profitable long arbitrage opportunities. Parachain slot auctions historically drive sustained positive funding as traders establish leveraged positions to capture DOT price appreciation. Weekend periods show reduced volatility in funding rates due to lower institutional activity, though retail-driven movements can still create arbitrage windows."}]]}]
6:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Arbitrage Opportunities and Strategies"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Cross-exchange arbitrage between Bluefin and centralized exchanges like Binance or OKX often yields 2-8 basis points per hour due to different user bases and settlement mechanics. Long-funding arbitrage works particularly well during Polkadot upgrade cycles when perpetual premiums spike above spot prices. The Sui blockchain's sub-second finality enables rapid position adjustments, allowing traders to capitalize on funding rate convergence opportunities. Multi-timeframe strategies can exploit the hourly settlement frequency by entering positions 10-15 minutes before funding calculations."}]]}]
7:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Management Considerations"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Sui network congestion during high-activity periods can impact order execution and funding settlement timing, requiring buffer margins for position management. DOT's correlation with Bitcoin and Ethereum means broader crypto market movements can quickly invalidate funding arbitrage positions through directional price action. Smart contract risks on Bluefin include potential bugs in the funding rate calculation logic or settlement mechanisms, though the protocol has undergone extensive auditing. Liquidity depth for DOT/USDT can thin during extreme market conditions, leading to slippage that erodes arbitrage profits and requires careful position sizing."}]]}]
8:["$","$Ld",null,{"items":[{"question":"How often does Bluefin settle DOT/USDT funding payments?","answer":"Bluefin settles funding payments every hour on the hour for DOT/USDT perpetuals. The funding rate is calculated based on the 8-hour time-weighted average premium, then divided by 8 for hourly payments, providing more frequent settlement opportunities than traditional 8-hour cycles."},{"question":"What are the minimum position sizes for DOT funding arbitrage on Bluefin?","answer":"Bluefin supports fractional DOT positions with no enforced minimum size, though gas costs on Sui make positions below $100 economically inefficient. The order book model allows for precise position sizing to match arbitrage opportunities across different exchanges."},{"question":"How does Sui blockchain affect DOT perpetual trading compared to Ethereum-based DEXs?","answer":"Sui's parallel execution enables faster order matching and settlement for DOT perpetuals, typically processing transactions in under 3 seconds versus 12+ seconds on Ethereum. Lower gas costs also make smaller arbitrage positions viable, though the newer ecosystem means less overall liquidity depth."},{"question":"Can I hedge DOT staking rewards using Bluefin perpetuals?","answer":"Yes, DOT perpetuals on Bluefin can effectively hedge price exposure while maintaining staking rewards from underlying DOT holdings. The funding rate often compensates for the 10-14% annual staking yield, creating a market-neutral strategy for large DOT holders."}]}]
